Hurricane Ian Hits Florida #florida #usa  Hurricane Ian is now making landfall in Florida. It is on the cusp of being a category 5 hurricane with sustained 155 mph winds. The storm surge has been reported to be 18 feet tall. Ian is now 24 miles wide and is the 5th strongest hurricane to ever make landfall in the US.  This is the most serious Hurricane to hit Florida since Hurricane Michael in 2018. Michael was a category 5 hurricane. Ian is still category 4 but experts say there is not real difference between Cat 4 and 5 for Ian given the current state that the hurricane is in.  #hurricane #tampa #hurricaneian #keywest #floridastorm #ian

Caught a mom and baby in the spring run @green_cove_springs. There was a herd of manatees at the mouth of the spring and in the run. They seemed to be seeking refuge from the waves as well as taking the opportunity to enter the run with the higher water. I was sure to keep my distance and use my zoom. Every human there was very respectful to the wildlife and making sure they were not in distress. There were approximately 10-15 manatees that we could see in the mouth of the spring and the St. John's River and the run itself. We do get manatees in this spot frequently, but I've never seen this many at once. As you can see, there is a young manatee with the larger one. The adult manatee has many propeller marks on its tail. It is so important to keep these amazing creatures safe. Nature is fearsome and awesome. We hope these precious manatees are safe from Hurricane Ian as well as all of the residents of Florida.  **Green Cove Spring is a natural spring, however it has largely been turned into a man-made feature as it feeds a public swimming pool which washes out into the run. I always wonder what the spring would look like today if it hadn't been taken over by man. Perhaps these manatees could seek refuge further on into the spring‚Ä¶We still appreciate it in it's current form. #fyp #Hurricane #hurricaneian #huricaneian2022 #manatee #manatees

Updates on the Key West chicken and the Southernmost Point post-Hurricane Ian. So many of you were concerned about the roosters and chickens, understandably so! These island chickens are resilient little birds and were out and about the moment Ian passed. They were up before the sun this morning waking the island and are doing their part in the clean-up efforts. Key West is strong. The island clean up is well underway and we are grateful to be a part is amazing community. As we begin our clean up efforts we continue to think of those still dealing with Ian. The footage out of South Florida is truly devestating. We will post ways to support those impacted as we gather the info. Many of you have also asked about travel to Key West and/or the Florida Keys. We are gathering info on that as well. Key West airport is open as of this morning (9/29). Many beaches and parks are closed for clean up. Openings are TBD. Bars, restaurants and shops are opening as they can depending on damage. We will be out on the island today assessing and reporting. Thank you for being here with us, supporting everyone being impacted, for your care and concern about our island animals, and for your kindness.
